  </Rules>
  <Rules AnalyzerId="System.Runtime.Analyzers" RuleNamespace="System.Runtime.Analyzers">
    <!-- CA1027 - MarkEnumsWithFlags: Forgetting to add a Flags attribute to an enumeration where appropriate is common.
    This rule is very accurate and useful in detecting these cases. -->
    <Rule Id="CA1027" Action="Warning" />
    <!-- CA1813 - AvoidUnsealedAttributes: Hardly anyone would think to do this without the warning to prompt for sealing
    custom attribute types. Since we're probably never going to use inheritance on custom attributes, or if we do the base
    attribute should probably be abstract anyway, or even if it logically isn't, it'll be in a framework level component
    somewhere and this rule can, and should, be suppressed with a comment explaining why this design choice was made, this
    rule will help us make a small improvement with little effort, and no real drawbacks. -->
    <Rule Id="CA1813" Action="Warning" />
    <!-- CA2217 - DoNotMarkEnumsWithFlags: This rule would be great if it did what it's documented to do, which is to
    trigger if any member of an enumeration marked with the Flags attribute isn't a power of two or a combination of
    other members. Unfortunately this rule currently goes a bit further, and also explicitly triggers if any power of
    two flag values are "skipped" between the upper and lower defined values. This doesn't allow cases such as reserving
    bits on the enumeration, or deprecating and later removing entries from the enumeration which are then free for
    re-use. In both cases this rule would trigger, as it wants a flags enumeration to be a pure run of consecutive bits.
    Since this is frequently in direct opposition to an existing practical reality an enumeration might be representing,
    or intentional future planning when the enumeration is being created, this rule is likely to frequently suggest a
    poor modification. Since the more common case of an enumeration omitting a flags attribute when it should be present
    is covered by other rules, we don't lose much by disabling this. -->
    <Rule Id="CA2217" Action="Hidden" />
  </Rules>
  <Rules AnalyzerId="System.Runtime.CSharp.Analyzers" RuleNamespace="System.Runtime.CSharp.Analyzers">
    <!-- CA1009 - DefineAccessorsForAttributeArguments: This is simply good practice. Custom attributes are designed for
    inspection via code. Having attribute constructor arguments implies those arguments are meaningful. Not exposing those
    argument values from the attribute itself doesn't make much sense. -->
    <Rule Id="CA1019" Action="Warning" />
    <!-- CA1309 - UseOrdinalStringComparison: We turn this rule on by default, because we want to encourage culture-aware
    handling of strings throughout the product. Code should be explicit about whether culture settings are being applied for
    string operations or not, and since the default is to apply them, and this is rarely what we want, we enable this rule
    to aim for explicit inclusion or exclusion of culture settings for string operations in all cases. -->
    <Rule Id="CA1309" Action="Warning" />
    <!-- CA1820 - TestForEmptyStringsUsingStringLength: This rule is a bit pedantic by itself, and there is no performance
    implication from using an equality check for empty strings anymore, but given that we've chosen to enable CA1309, it
    makes sense to enable this rule too, so that we consistently warn on the use of default equality tests against strings. -->
    <Rule Id="CA1820" Action="Warning" />
    <!-- CA2213 - DisposableFieldsShouldBeDisposed: Unfortunately this rule currently triggers on fields that are populated
    via constructor parameters, and are merely shared with, not owned by the class. If this is changed in the future this
    rule can be reactivated, however note that CA1001 also checks for disposable members, and unlike this rule it only fires
    for internally constructed members, establishing ownership, ignoring ones passed as arguments to methods. That being the
    case, CA2213 isn't required. -->
    <Rule Id="CA2213" Action="Hidden" />
  </Rules>
  <Rules AnalyzerId="System.Runtime.InteropServices.Analyzers" RuleNamespace="System.Runtime.InteropServices.Analyzers">
    <!-- CA1401 - PInvokesShouldNotBeVisible: Where Win32 interop is required, it is better to expose public access to
    PInvoke methods via a single library than it is to scatter separate direct PInvoke usage in dozens of disparate
    places throughout the codebase. In this case it is best to expose the PInvoke methods publicly from a static helper
    class specifically provided for this purpose. That being the case, we disable this rule here. -->
    <Rule Id="CA1401" Action="None" />
  </Rules>
</RuleSet>
